SIMPLE: up
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Up
<hw>Up</hw> <pr>(⟦ucr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>up</ets>,
<ets>upp</ets>, <ets>⟦umac⟧p</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>up</ets>,
<ets>op</ets>, D. <ets>op</ets>, OS. <ets>⟦umac⟧p</ets>, OHG.
<ets>⟦umac⟧f</ets>, G. <ets>auf</ets>, Icel. & Sw. <ets>upp</ets>, Dan.
<ets>op</ets>, Goth. <ets>iup</ets>, and probably to E. <ets>over</ets>.
See <er>Over</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Aloft; on high; in a direction contrary to that of
gravity; toward or in a higher place or position; above; -- the opposite
of <ant>down</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But <qex>up</qex> or down,⟦br⟧
By center or eccentric, hard to tell.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence, in many derived uses, specifically:
--</specif>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>From a lower to a higher position, literally or
figuratively; as, from a recumbent or sitting position; from the mouth,
toward the source, of a river; from a dependent or inferior condition;
from concealment; from younger age; from a quiet state, or the like; --
used with verbs of motion expressed or implied.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But they presumed to go <qex>up</qex> unto the hilltop.</q>
<rj><qau>Num. xiv. 44.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am afflicted and ready to die from my youth <qex>up</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. lxxxviii. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Up</qex> rose the sun, and <qex>up</qex> rose Emelye.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have wrought ourselves <qex>up</qex> into this degree of
Christian indifference.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>In a higher place or position, literally or
figuratively; in the state of having arisen; in an upright, or nearly
upright, position; standing; mounted on a horse; in a condition of
elevation, prominence, advance, proficiency, excitement, insurrection,
or the like; -- used with verbs of rest, situation, condition, and the
like; <as>as, to be <ex>up</ex> on a hill; the lid of the box was
<ex>up</ex>; prices are <ex>up</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And when the sun was <qex>up</qex>, they were scorched.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xiii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those that were <qex>up</qex> themselves kept others low.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Helen was <qex>up</qex> -- was she?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Rebels there are <qex>up</qex>,⟦br⟧
And put the Englishmen unto the sword.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His name was <qex>up</qex> through all the adjoining provinces,
even to Italy and Rome; many desiring to see who he was that could
withstand so many years the Roman puissance.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou hast fired me; my soul's <qex>up</qex> in arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grief and passion are like floods raised in little brooks by a
sudden rain; they are quickly <qex>up</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A general whisper ran among the country people, that Sir Roger was
<qex>up</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us, then, be <qex>up</qex> and doing,⟦br⟧
With a heart for any fate.</q> <rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>To or in a position of equal advance or equality;
not short of, back of, less advanced than, away from, or the like; --
usually followed by <xex>to</xex> or <xex>with</xex>; <as>as, to be
<ex>up</ex> to the chin in water; to come <ex>up</ex> with one's
companions; to come <ex>up</ex> with the enemy; to live <ex>up</ex> to
engagements</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As a boar was whetting his teeth, <qex>up</qex> comes a fox to
him.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>To or in a state of completion; completely; wholly;
quite; <as>as, in the phrases to eat <ex>up</ex>; to drink <ex>up</ex>;
to burn <ex>up</ex>; to sum <ex>up</ex>; etc.; to shut <ex>up</ex> the
eyes or the mouth; to sew <ex>up</ex> a rent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Some phrases of this kind are now obsolete; as, to spend
<xex>up</xex> (<au>Prov. xxi. 20</au>); to kill <xex>up</xex> (<au>B.
Jonson</au>).</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <def>Aside, so as not to be in use; <as>as, to lay
<ex>up</ex> riches; put <ex>up</ex> your weapons</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Up</xex> is used elliptically for <xex>get
up</xex>, <xex>rouse up</xex>, etc., expressing a command or
exhortation. ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Up</xex>, and let us be going.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Judg.
xix. 28.</au></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Up</qex>, <qex>up</qex>, my friend! and quit your books,⟦br⟧
Or surely you 'll grow double.</q> <rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>It is all up with him</b></col>, <cd>it is all over with
him; he is lost.</cd> -- <col><b>The time is up</b></col>, <cd>the
allotted time is past.</cd> -- <col><b>To be up in</b></col>, <cd>to be
informed about; to be versed in.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Anxious that their sons
<xex>should be</xex> well <xex>up in</xex> the superstitions of two
thousand years ago.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>H. Spencer.</au> -- <col><b>To be up
to</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To be equal to, or prepared for; as, he
<xex>is up to</xex> the business, or the emergency.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To be engaged in; to purpose,
with the idea of doing ill or mischief; <as>as, I don't know what he's
<ex>up to</ex></as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To blow
up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To inflate; to distend.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>To destroy by an explosion from beneath.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To
explode; <as>as, the boiler <ex>blew up</ex></as>.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd>
<cd>To reprove angrily; to scold.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark> --
<col><b>To bring up</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Bring</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To come up with</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Come</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To cut up</b></col>.
<cd>See under <er>Cut</er>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To
draw up</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Draw</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos></cd> --
<col><b>To grow up</b></col>, <cd>to grow to maturity.</cd> --
<col><b>Up anchor</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the order to man the
windlass preparatory to hauling up the anchor.</cd> -- <col><b>Up and
down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>First up, and then down; from one state
or position to another. See under <er>Down</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos></cd>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>Fortune . . . led him <qex>up and down</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>Vertical; perpendicular; -- said of
the cable when the anchor is under, or nearly under, the hawse hole, and
the cable is taut.</cd> <au>Totten.</au> -- <col><b>Up helm</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>the order given to move the tiller toward the
upper, or windward, side of a vessel.</cd> -- <col><b>Up to
snuff</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Snuff</er>.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark>
-- <col><b>What is up?</b></col> <cd>What is going on?</cd>
<mark>[Slang]</mark></cs> <-- what's up? what's happening? -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Up</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Up
<hw>Up</hw>, <pos>prep.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>From a lower to a higher
place on, upon, or along; at a higher situation upon; at the top
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In going <qex>up</qex> a hill, the knees will be most weary; in
going down, the thihgs.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>From the coast towards the interior of, as a
country; from the mouth towards the source of, as a stream; <as>as, to
journey <ex>up</ex> the country; to sail <ex>up</ex> the
Hudson</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Upon.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Up</xex>
pain of death.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Up</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Up
<hw>Up</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The state of being up or above; a state
of elevation, prosperity, or the like; -- rarely occurring except in the
phrase <xex>ups and downs</xex>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ups and downs</b></col>, <cd>alternate states of
elevation and depression, or of prosperity and the contrary.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They had their <qex>ups and downs</qex> of fortune.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Up</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Up
<hw>Up</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Inclining up; tending or going up;
upward; <as>as, an <ex>up</ex> look; an <ex>up</ex> grade; the
<ex>up</ex> train</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Upas</ent>⟦br⟧
